ce:section.ce:para:
Crystal violet (CV) is a basic cationic dye that is easily dissolved in water and is commonly used as coloring agent, packaging materials, paper, and textile industries. It causes major health problems in humans and aquatic animals including cancer, skin irritations, eye burns, mutations, and allergic dermatitis. CV is used in the fields of microbiology, diagnostics, medical surgery, and aquaculture. Even though, CV is widely found as a pollutant in industry effluents, reducing CV is both ecologically and physiologically important (Auta and Hameed, 2014). The prominent absorption peak of CV shows at 598 nm (λmax
                        ) and it is a (purple) violet-colored solution. For this reduction, the reaction takes up 2.50 mL of dye, and freshly prepared 0.20 mL of NaBH4 (ice-cooled condition) was added the intensity is slightly decreased in 120 min. After 120 min there is no significant change even when the reaction time is increased as shown in Fig. 8
                        (a). The synthesized NBCNDs (30 μL) catalyst was added into the reaction containing CV dye and reducing agent the intensity of dye is slowly decreased at a linear time interval and the reaction completed within 14 min Fig. 8(b) which confirms that the NBCNDs act as an effective catalyst in the reduction process of CV. The obtained linear plot yielded R2 and rate constant values (k) of 0.9878 and 0.1521 min−1, respectively Fig. 8(c). The m/z value of pure CV dye is 407.9 Fig. 8(d), but after the reduction the m/z value of 373.5 of the colorless solution is depicted in Fig. 8(e), indicating that CV was effectively reduced using BDCNDs catalyst. The (GC-MS) spectroscopic results are used to determine the potential structures of the obtained reduction product. Compared to earlier reported catalysts such as ZnO, TiO2, CdS, SnO2, etc.,
